# BMS Hostel Platform — Current Implementation Assessment Report

> **Generated:** 2026-03-01 | **Scope:** Full repo (`d:\Apps\hostel\BMS_hostel`) end-to-end
> **Analyst:** Antigravity (no code was modified)

---

## 1. Executive Summary

The BMS Hostel Platform is a Turborepo monorepo containing a **NestJS REST API** (modular monolith), a **Next.js 14 admin portal** (App Router), and an **Expo React Native mobile app**. It is designed for Indian college hostel management — covering registration, room allotment, gate management, leave, complaints, notices, violations, and fees.

**What is solidly implemented (production-ready API layer):**
- Full JWT auth with refresh-token rotation and reuse detection (`apps/api/src/auth`)
- 11-role RBAC via `JwtAuthGuard` + `RolesGuard` + `PermissionsGuard` applied to all protected routes
- 19 backend modules are wired and importable; all controllers have real service calls backed by Prisma
- Prisma schema is fully designed across 6 phases — 20 models, all migrated
- Comprehensive audit logging via `AuditInterceptor` on every mutating endpoint
- Dashboard stats endpoint pulling live data across all modules

**What is stub/partial:**
- The **web UI** (`apps/web`) has a full dashboard shell with 16 sub-sections, but the `dashboard/page.tsx` is a large single-file implementation — it needs verification whether all 16 sections hit the API or use mock data
- The **mobile app** (`apps/mobile`) has only 3 screens: `_layout.tsx`, `index.tsx`, `login.tsx` — it is a placeholder shell
- **Notifications are stored in DB** but no email/SMS/push delivery is implemented (channels: EMAIL, SMS, PUSH all in schema but no transport wired)
- **Payment integration** (Razorpay) is commented out in `.env.example` — not implemented
- **File uploads** use local `diskStorage` (`uploads/` folder on disk), not S3-compatible cloud storage
- **Redis is provisioned** (docker-compose.yml) but **not consumed** — no BullMQ queues, no caching in Phase 1

**Critical security observation:**
- File upload endpoint (`POST /api/v1/uploads/photo`) does **not configure a file filter** for photos — only the document endpoint has a `fileFilter`. A non-image file can be uploaded as a photo.

