## 7. Risks & Hotspots

### 🔴 Critical

| # | Issue | Evidence | Severity |
|---|---|---|---|
| C1 | **Upload photo endpoint has no file type filter** — `uploadPhoto()` in `uploads.controller.ts:42` uses `FileInterceptor('file')` with no `fileFilter`, unlike `uploadDocument()` (line 64) which validates extensions. An attacker can upload any file type (including `.exe`, `.html`, `.svg`) as a "photo" and access it via the static asset route. | `apps/api/src/uploads/uploads.controller.ts:28–59` | Critical |
| C2 | **Uploaded files served from local disk with no access control** — `main.ts:17` serves `uploads/` as static assets with prefix `/uploads/`. Any file URL is publicly accessible without auth. Combined with C1, this is a stored file exposure risk. | `apps/api/src/main.ts:16–19` | Critical |

### 🟠 High

| # | Issue | Evidence | Severity |
|---|---|---|---|
| H1 | **No password reset / forgot password flow** — No endpoint exists (no `POST /auth/forgot-password` or `POST /auth/reset-password`). Users who forget their password can only be reset by an admin via `PATCH /users/:id`. This is a major gap for a live system. | Confirmed by searching entire `src/` — not found | High |
| H2 | **Role assignment has no API endpoint** — The RBAC matrix specifies `ROLE_ASSIGN` / `ROLE_REVOKE` permissions but there is no `/users/:id/roles` or `/roles` endpoint. Role assignment can only be done via direct DB seed or Prisma Studio. | `docs/rbac-matrix.md:30-31`, no route found | High |
| H3 | **Dashboard controller queries DB directly** — `DashboardController` injects `PrismaService` directly and executes 14+ parallel queries in a single request, plus a 7-iteration loop (one query per day for login trend). This is an **N+1 loop query** (`dashboard.controller.ts:97–116`). At scale, this single endpoint could be a bottleneck. | `apps/api/src/dashboard/dashboard.controller.ts:97–116` | High |
| H4 | **Token storage in localStorage** — `assumptions.md:25` explicitly states "tokens stored in localStorage for Phase 1." This exposes access tokens to XSS attacks in the web app. | `docs/assumptions.md:52` | High |
| H5 | **Seed credentials committed to `.env.example`** — `SEED_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@bms.local`, `SEED_ADMIN_PASSWORD=Admin@123456` are in `apps/api/.env.example` and root `.env.example`. If this file is committed to a public/shared repo, default credentials are exposed. | `apps/api/.env.example:21-22`, `.env.example:55-56` | High |

### 🟡 Medium

| # | Issue | Evidence | Severity |
|---|---|---|---|
| M1 | **Notification delivery not implemented** — `Notification.channel` supports EMAIL, SMS, PUSH, IN_APP. Only IN_APP is stored. No SMTP, SMS provider, or push integration wired. SMTP/SMS vars are commented in `.env.example`. Users set to be notified about gate events, violations, etc. silently receive nothing externally. | `apps/api/src/notifications/`, `.env.example:47-52` | Medium |
| M2 | **Leave controller filters by `user.roles` using `Array.includes` on a plain array** — `leave.controller.ts:52`: `user.roles?.includes('STUDENT')`. If the JWT payload doesn't populate `roles` as a flat string array, this silently returns all leave data to a student who should only see their own. Same pattern in complaints and violations controllers. | `leave.controller.ts:52,78`, `complaints.controller.ts:53`, `violations.controller.ts:79` | Medium |
| M3 | **No pagination on audit log default limit is 200** — `audit.controller.ts:28`: `@Max(200)` allows fetching up to 200 audit records per page. This is acceptable but the audit table can grow unbounded with no archival/cleanup strategy documented. | `audit.controller.ts:28` | Medium |
| M4 | **DashboardController bypasses `DashboardModule`** — It injects `PrismaService` directly rather than delegating to individual module services. This breaks module encapsulation and makes it hard to add caching or permission granularity later. | `dashboard.controller.ts:13` | Medium |
| M5 | **Mess Management is documented but completely absent** — Architecture doc (`architecture.md:46`) shows a "Mess Module" as a core module. No `mess/` directory exists in `src/`, it's not in `app.module.ts`, and the RBAC matrix defines `MESS_MANAGE` and `MESS_SCAN` permissions that have no enforcing code. | `apps/api/src/` — no `mess` directory | Medium |
| M6 | **`apps/api/.env` committed** — The `apps/api/` directory has a `.env` file present (shown in the file listing). This is different from `.env.example`. If it contains real secrets, it should not be tracked. | `apps/api/.env` (472 bytes) | Medium |

### 🔵 Low

| # | Issue | Evidence | Severity |
|---|---|---|---|
| L1 | **Violations controller has no POST** — Violations are auto-created by the gate service. If there's a bug in gate logic, violations cannot be manually corrected through the API. | `violations.controller.ts` — no `@Post()` | Low |
| L2 | **Rate limiting global defaults may be too permissive** — Global throttler: 10/s short, 30/min medium (`app.module.ts:36-45`). Auth endpoints override this (5/min login, 10/min refresh). But general API endpoints under `SUPER_ADMIN` roles are not additionally throttled. | `app.module.ts:34-45` | Low |
| L3 | **Swagger version mismatch** — `main.ts:57` sets API version `0.2.0` but `health.controller.ts:22` returns `version: '0.1.0'`. Minor inconsistency. | `main.ts:57`, `health.controller.ts:22` | Low |
| L4 | **Redis provisioned but idle** — `docker-compose.yml` starts Redis; it occupies memory/resources but is unused in Phase 1. No BullMQ queue, no cache. | `docs/assumptions.md:46` | Low |
| L5 | **No i18n — hardcoded English strings** — Error messages, constants are English-only. Not a current risk given `assumptions.md:29`, but worth noting for future. | `docs/assumptions.md:59` | Low |

